  "prompt": "How are polar covalent bonds formed?",
  "response": "Polar covalent bonds are formed when two atoms share electrons unequally due to a difference in their electronegativities. Electronegativity is a measure of an atom's ability to attract and hold onto electrons. \n\nHere's how polar covalent bonds are formed:\n\n1. **Difference in Electronegativity**: When two different atoms come together to form a bond, one atom may have a higher electronegativity than the other. This difference in electronegativity causes the shared electrons to be pulled closer to the more electronegative atom.\n\n2. **Unequal Sharing of Electrons**: In a polar covalent bond, the atom with higher electronegativity attracts the shared electrons more strongly. As a result, the electron cloud is distorted, leading to an unequal sharing of electrons.\n\n3. **Partial Charges**: The atom with a higher electronegativity gains a partial negative charge (\u03b4\u2212) because it has a greater electron density around it, while the less electronegative atom has a partial positive charge (\u03b4+) due to the reduced electron density. This difference in charge distribution creates a dipole moment in the bond.\n\n4. **Examples**: Common examples of polar covalent bonds include the bonds in water (H\u2082O), where oxygen is more electronegative than hydrogen, leading to a polar bond. This property is responsible for many of the unique characteristics of water.\n\nIn summary, polar covalent bonds result from the unequal sharing of electrons between two atoms with different electronegativities, leading to the creation of partial charges on the atoms involved.",
